# Intuition
Let's solve a very basic problem, like if we have only two nodes in linked list something like this
![Screenshot from 2023-05-16 21-18-05.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1d8eaf14-3512-4e3d-bc46-57e3dd6746f0_1684253393.1944199.png)

Then, our approach is divided into 3 steps
* ***Step1*** Set CurrNode's next to NextNode's next
![Screenshot from 2023-05-16 21-21-08.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0409e8be-a0f4-49de-8ca8-7cf14ba869be_1684253489.2341714.png)

* ***Step2*** Set NextNode's next to CurrNode
![Screenshot from 2023-05-16 21-25-06.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/362d02de-00fc-4e49-a1c2-2c80404593c9_1684253531.1400237.png)

* ***Step3*** We are done with swapping now, we have to return the NextNode as our new head.
![Screenshot from 2023-05-16 21-28-32.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/dc72258a-ac45-4dfe-8045-4d4cb40b279a_1684253573.5092244.png)

We have solved our problem, now we have to implement this logic

# Approach
* If Head node is empty or Head's next is empty, return Head ecause we don't have anything to perform our logic

* Set NextNode to Head->next

* Now, Set recursion result to Head->next

* Now, Set NextNode->next to head

* Finally, return the NextNode which is our ans.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$
Where n is the length of the linked list.
`Note: We have traversed only half linked list.`

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(1)$$
Because we haven't consumed any extra space.
`Note: We consumed some auxiliary space for recursion stack.`

