# Approach
The provided code implements a method called `swapPairs` in a class. This method swaps adjacent pairs of nodes in a singly linked list. Here's the breakdown of the approach used:

1. The method takes a parameter `head`, which represents the head node of the linked list.

2. The first step is to check if the `head` is `null` or if there is only one node in the list (`head.next == null`). In either case, there is no need to swap any nodes, so the method returns the `head` as it is.

3. If there are at least two nodes in the list, a new dummy node called `ans` is created with a value of 0. The `ans.next` is set to the original `head` of the list. This dummy node serves as the new head of the modified list, which will make it easier to handle the edge case of swapping the first two nodes.

4. Two pointers, `temp` and `temp1`, are initialized with `head` and `ans` respectively. These pointers will be used to traverse the list and perform the node swaps.

5. The main loop runs as long as `temp` is not `null` and `temp.next` is not `null`. This loop processes pairs of nodes in the list until there are no more pairs left to swap.

6. Inside the loop, a new node `forw` is assigned as the next node after `temp`. This node represents the second node of the current pair.

7. The following steps perform the swapping:
   - `temp.next` is updated to skip the second node (`forw`).
   - `forw.next` is set to `temp`, making `temp` the second node in the pair.
   - `temp1.next` is set to `forw`, connecting the swapped pair to the modified list.
   - `temp1` is updated to `temp`, so it now represents the last node that was swapped.
   - `temp` is updated to `temp.next` to move to the next pair of nodes.

8. Once the loop is completed, the modified list is obtained by accessing `ans.next`. This returns the head of the modified linked list.

9. Finally, the modified list is returned as the result.

Overall, this approach uses iterative traversal and manipulation of the linked list to swap adjacent pairs of nodes. It employs a dummy node to simplify the handling of the first pair.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
    - The time complexity of the swapPairs method is O(n).
- Space complexity:
    - The space complexity of the method is O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public ListNode swapPairs(ListNode head) {
        if (head == null || head.next == null) {
            return head;
        }        
        ListNode ans = new ListNode(0);
        ans.next = head;       
        ListNode temp = head;
        ListNode temp1 = ans;

        while (temp != null && temp.next != null) {
            ListNode forw = temp.next;
            temp.next = forw.next;
            forw.next = temp;
            temp1.next = forw;
            temp1 = temp;
            temp = temp.next;
        }

        return ans.next;
    }
}

```

